title: For Sale:  PWS MK118 Primary Weapons Systems 18" 5.56 .223 AR
postcontent:
With AR refinements that make it as reliable as an AK47 but as accurate as the best semi-automatic rifles, the gas piston Primary Weapons System Mark 118 is a favorite of knowledgeable precision shooters.

PWS started with a clean sheet of paper in designing the MK118. Start with the PWS long-stroke piston sytem which combines the agility of the AR-15 with the reliability of the AK-47 into a sleek and efficient design. By utilizing a one piece design, the PWS piston system creates a purely gas to metal operation, rather than metal on metal contact that you may see in other designs. The PWS four position adjustable gas block restricts gasses, rather than venting them from the side. This allows the unused gas to exit from the front of the gun, rather than the sides of the gas block, resulting in a more quiet operation.

The PWS QPQ Isonited Barrel is made using only the highest quality chromoly barrel blank. It's turned at PWS and then treated with QPQ Isonite for increased surface hardness and corrosion resistance. MK1 rifles are chambered in .223 Wylde, which accommodates both 5.56 Nato and .223 Remington without sacrificing accuracy. The barrel features a 1:8 twist, which accommodates 55gr through 75gr .223 round with a high degree of accuracy

The PWS Bolt Carrier Group is machined from tool steel at strict tolerances, then Nickel Teflon coated for durability and to reduce friction. It features an increased carrier mass to extend dwell time and delay unlock. As a result the PWS bolt carrier group allows chamber pressure to be greatly reduced for easier extraction. The PWS bolt system is Nickel Teflon coated and optimized for the .223 wylde chamber. It features a small assist spring for system assembly.

This rifles ergonomics match its mechanics. With all Magpul furniture, including a Magpul Precision Rifle/Sniper Stock, the MK118 includes the PWS Free Floated Handguard. PWS engineers designed a handguard which is ergonomic as well as durable. Featuring the KeyMod interface, the MK1 series handguard eliminates unnecessary weight and allows for a wide range of accessory placement. The picatinny top rail is extruded and then machined from aircraft grade 6061 aluminum, every handguard comes standard with a full-length Picatinny top rail and two 2 inch Picatinny sections.

Included is a 30 round Magpul PMAG and Magpul flip-up front and rear sights

Lightly Used Sig P224 SAS GEN2 40S&W, SA/DA SRT, SIGLITE Night Sights, 2-10rd and 2-12rd Mags. Payment Accepted: Cash or VISA/MC w/ 3.0% processing fee added.

The SIG SAUER P224 is the first true subcompact in its classic all-metal firearms line. Ideal for concealed or off-duty carry, the P224 offers all of the features expected. The SIG Anti-Snag (SAS) model, shown here, features a de-horned slide and frame, and the new ergonomically enhanced one-piece grip.

Based on the P229, one of the most prolific sidearms in federal law enforcement, the P224 takes the same hammer-fire reliability and lightweight all-metal frame with One Small Change that makes it an ideal concealed carry or back-up gun. The P224 is an especially good choice for those familiar with the SIG SAUER manual of arms.

Despite its small size, the P224 maintains a double-stack magazine for a capacity of 10 rounds of .40S&W giving the P224 a decided advantage over most subcompact competitors. The P224 accepts newer P229 magazines, allowing users to carry a full-size spare magazine as a backup to the flush-fit P224 magazine. Law enforcement officers will appreciate not having to carry separate magazines solely for their backup guns.

“Almost 80 percent of federal law enforcement agencies have chosen the P229 for its durability, reliability and safety,” said Ron Cohen, SIG SAUER President and Chief Executive Officer. “The P224 may be cut down in size, but it hasn’t lost an ounce of these performance features.” 

Traditional DA/SA trigger, short-reset trigger (SRT) and full-size SIGLITE Night Sights allow the P224 to deliver pinpoint accuracy, which can be a challenge in most subcompacts.

title: For Sale:  $500
postcontent:
100 YEAR OLD Stevens pump shotgun: 20 ga., 30” barrel, 2 ½”-3” shells, full choke
On the receiver: “J. STEVENS ARMS & TOOL CO.
   Chicopee Falls, Mass., USA
   PATS APR. 12—10-APR. 2-12      SN18649
This was my step-dad’s “Turkey Shoot” gun in the 1950’s; and it was old then, but it remains in good condition--very little pitting, it operates smoothly and is a shooter.
"The No. 200 was a hammerless pump 20 gauge which could handle 2 1/2", 2 3/4" or 3" shells at a time when most 20 gauge shotguns were single shot "boy's" guns which could only handle the 2 1/2 inch shell. It was only made from about 1911 to about 1914.
Based on serial numbers, there were only about 20,000 made. The highest serial number observed on any internet forum or auction post is in the 19,8xx range. This number is correct by the usual other sources. 
The Stevens No. 200 is a complicated gun.  It operates with a short bolt which is held in place by a tilting "carrier".  It also has two blades which, when the pump is acuated, first keep the shell from rolling out of the partially closed action, and second, seals the hole behind the bolt. 
There is a tang mounted safety like on better grade double barrel shotguns.  It weighs from 5 3/4 to 6 1/2 pounds, depending for the barrel length.  All barrels are choked "Full" unless the barrel is marked otherwise."

FACE-TO-FACE transaction only.

title: For Sale:  STEVENS MODEL 200 20 GA. PUMP SHOTGUN
postcontent:
100 YEAR OLD Stevens pump shotgun: 20 ga., 30” barrel, 2 ½”-3” shells
On the receiver: “J. STEVENS ARMS & TOOL CO.
   Chicopee Falls, Mass., USA
   PATS APR. 12—10-APR. 2-12     SN18649
This was my step-dad’s “Turkey Shoot” gun in the 1950’s; and it was old then, but it remains in good condition--very little pitting, it operates smoothly and is a shooter.  CONTACT FOR MORE PICS.
"The No. 200 was a hammerless pump 20 gauge which could handle 2 1/2", 2 3/4" or 3" shells at a time when most 20 gauge shotguns were single shot "boy's" guns which could only handle the 2 1/2 inch shell. It was only made from about 1911 to about 1914.
Based on serial numbers, there were only about 20,000 made. The highest serial number observed on any internet forum or auction post is in the 19,8xx range. This number is correct by the usual other sources. 
The Stevens No. 200 is a complicated gun.  It operates with a short bolt which is held in place by a tilting "carrier".  It also has two blades which, when the pump is acuated, first keep the shell from rolling out of the partially closed action, and second, seals the hole behind the bolt. 
There is a tang mounted safety like on better grade double barrel shotguns.  It weighs from 5 3/4 to 6 1/2 pounds, depending for the barrel length.  All barrels are choked "Full" unless the barrel is marked otherwise."
COMES WITH THE RARE TAKEDOWN WRENCH

FACE-TO-FACE transaction only.

In 2008, Rossi was acquired by Taurus and together the two firms work to improve products and create new lines.
The Winchester Model 1892 was a lever action repeating rifle designed by John Browning as a smaller, lighter version of his large-frame Model 1886– which replaced the Model 1873 as the company’s lever-action for smaller dual-purpose rounds such as the 44-40. Cowboys on the frontier found it convenient to carry a rifle and a revolver chambered with the same ammunition. When asked by Winchester to design an improved pistol caliber lever action, John Browning said he would have the prototype completed in under a month– or it would be free. Two weeks later, Browning had a functioning prototype of the Model 92.
The Model 1892 has become an indelible icon of Western mythology through its use in hundreds of motion pictures and television shows. Even though Winchester ended production of the Model 92 in 1938, Rossi continues to manufacture a faithful reproduction of this historic rifle to this day.
The Rossi R92-68016 lever action rifle features a 16″ barrel, STAINLESS STEEL finish, adjustable buckhorn rear sight, Brass Bead front sight, hardwood furniture with recoil absorbing butt-pad, 8+1 capacity tubular magazine, and a manual safety. These rifles are the ultimate companion to your .454 Casull revolver!

title: For Trade:  Yugo m59/66 SKS trade for mountain bike
postcontent:
Looking to trade my sks for a nice mountain bike.  

I bought this rifle from Vance's in Columbus a few years ago.  I believe it was unfired surplus back then as the bore was nice and shiny and it was covered with a good amount of cosmoline.
Since then i've removed most of the cosmoline and i've put maybe.... ohh...... 200 rounds through it.  Something like that.  The bore is a bit darker now and there is some frost but the rifling remains strong and it remains a good shooter.  We're not talkin' old abused mosin nagant territory here, just shooter-condition sks territory, if you will.
I've tried to clean it well after shooting.  Occasionally i'd clean the gas piston to make sure that was all fine and good.  Contact me if you want a picture of the bolt face and bolt carrier.  I cleaned these after each outing but they sport a bit of rust now regardless.
The sight hood is slightly bent from a time when the rifle fell over from an upright position.
The threads on the cleaning rod that screw it into the receiver are stripped so it doesn't screw in there, but it still serves as a cleaning rod... of course.

The serial numbers on the receiver, bolt carrier, bolt, stock, and magazine all match.  The rifle also sports some electro-penned numbers along with the factory stamped numbers... i suspect from being arsenal refurbished/stored.  The numbers on the bolt, bolt carrier, receiver, stock and magazine are all stamped from the factory when the rifle was built and are not force-matched.
You will also receive two stripper clips, around 60 rounds of brass cased yugo surplus ammo, a sling if i can find it, the old yugo cleaning kit that stored in the butt of the stock, and a cute little "thanks for buying this sks!" thing from century arms that came with the rifle.

See my listing for my other yugo (an m57) if you're lookin' for one of those.

title: For Trade:  Trade yugo M57 TT-33 7.62x25 for a nice mountain bike
postcontent:
Looking to trade my yugo m-57 for a descent mountain bike.

Bought a couple years ago and put about 200 rounds through it.  It's a surplus/arsenal refurbished gun.  The serial numbers on the frame and slide match.  The number on the barrel matches the frame and slide but it is electro-penned and may be an arsenal force match.  The number on the hammer group is electro-penned and does not match.
The bore doesn't shine like new but it's not dark.  There's some rust in there but it isn't heavily pitted.  Perhaps slightly pitted.  Maybe minor pitting?  The rifling remains descent- not super strong, but not perfect.  That's probably not the best description you've ever read.. contact me for a picture of the bore if you like.
I'd describe it somewhere between dark frosty mosin nagant bore and sks-i-didn't-clean-once bore.

Picture shows the condition of the bluing well.  You can see some scratches on the frame from where that lever swings out when you want to disassemble the pistol.
It has that importer-installed safety.
It's a shooter... not perfect but it functions well and it's fun to shoot.

You'll also receive around 30-rounds of surplus 7.62x25 and the standard surplus yugo package that includes two magazines (9-rounds as this is an m-57), a leather holster, and a cleaning rod.
The surplus ammo IS the kind that you'll get occasional case-neck splits from.  It never bothered me and i don't think the gun cared either, but i feel like that's important to throw out there.

see my add for my other yugo (an sks this time) if you're lookin' for one of those are interested in both.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1911 you don't see everyday
postcontent: It's a commander size Israel Arms LTD M-5000. I have done a ton of research on these and can find very little info. They produced for only a few years. This one has the star of David stamped stamped on the inside of the slide and on the frame under the grips, which signifies that it was an earlier, more desirable, model made in Israel with forged match grade parts, the later models without this stamp were made from cast parts kits from the Philippines. It's 2tone with, with dove tailed sights, skeleton hammer & trigger, black checkered grips, 3 mags, and original wood grips. This is a reliable and accurate shooter, and has not seen a lot of rounds. I'll sell for $550obo, mostly looking to sell, but will entertain trade offers of other pistols, would like a sig p320c or sc, may look at full size, may need a little boot or extras depending on which model
